4","1503–1599":"1503–1599","1508–1535":"1508–1535","1594":"1594","1580":"1580","1591":"1591","1525":"1525","1503":"1503","Aug 1535":"August 1535","1535":"1535","1600":"1600","1523":"1523","1599":"1599","1610":"1610","1554":"1554","1542":"1542","1508":"1508","1529":"1529","1616":"1616","1527":"1527","Harrock, Lancashire":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Harrock, Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Northill, Bedfordshire, England":"Northill, Bedfordshire, England","Harrock, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Rigbye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Ribby in Lancashire, named with Old Scandanavian <i>hryggr</i> ‘ridge’ + <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village’. Compare   Rigsby  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Rigsby","meanings":["English: habitational name from Rigsby (Lincolnshire), probably from the genitive form of Old Norse <i>hryggr</i> ‘ridge’ + <i>bȳ</i> ‘farmstead, village’."]}]},{"name":"Susanna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament form (Luke 8:3) of the Hebrew name <i>Shoshana</i> (from <i>shoshan</i> ‘lily’, which in modern Hebrew also means ‘rose’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Suzannah","meanings":["New Testament form (Luke 8:3) of the Hebrew name <i>Shoshana</i> (from <i>shoshan</i> ‘lily’, which in modern Hebrew also means ‘rose’)."]},{"name":"Suzanna","meanings":["New Testament form (Luke 8:3) of the Hebrew name <i>Shoshana</i> (from <i>shoshan</i> ‘lily’, which in modern Hebrew also means ‘rose’)."]},{"name":"Susana","meanings":["From Hebrew.  See  <b>Susanna</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Susanna Jane Rigbye was born in 1525, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Nicholas Rigby IV, was 22 and her mother, Margaret Anderton, was 17. She had at least 1 son with John Wilkinson. She died in 1580, in Lancaster, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 55."},"et":{"1525–1580":"1525–1580","1523–1616":"1523–1616","1527–1610":"1527–1610","1554–1591":"1554–1591","1529–1600":"1529–1600","1542–1594":"1542–1594","1503–1599":"1503–1599","1508–1535":"1508–1535","1594":"1594","1580":"1580","1591":"1591","1525":"1525","1503":"1503","Aug 1535":"august 1535","1535":"1535","1600":"1600","1523":"1523","1599":"1599","1610":"1610","1554":"1554","1542":"1542","1508":"1508","1529":"1529","1616":"1616","1527":"1527","Harrock, Lancashire":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Harrock, Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Northill, Bedfordshire, England":"Northill, Bedfordshire, England","Harrock, Lancas